Figure 1

Note: Examples of how area under curve proportions are affected by both the selection of delay values as well as the degree of discounting. In the subplots above, the overall amount of discounting in each is the same (~75% of value) but the proportion of area under the curve to the maximum area is driven increasingly lower as the maximum delay increases.

Figure 2

Note: These two plots in this figure illustrate how modeled discounting processes can be used to focus on specific delays of interestseven if not directly assessed. The top plot shows the discounting data from three hypothetical experiments. In the bottom plot, the range of delays being targeted has been adjusted to match those from the study using PB-AUC (Study A), which cannot be adjusted.
